<HL>
   International:
   Brazil Signs IMF Letter,
   Will Resume Debt Talks
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRASILIA -- Brazil signed a letter of intent to the
International Monetary Fund and pledged to resume debt
renegotiations with creditors this month.
   The letter was the result of drawn-out negotiations that
reportedly nearly fell through over disagreement about a
token payment to creditors.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Economy Minister Zelia Cardoso de Mello said Brazil
wouldn't make any symbolic payment of arrears to creditors of
the country's $117 billion foreign debt, the largest in the
Third World.
   "We want a constructive, definitive and quick solution,"
the official said.
   In the letter, Brazil requested a standby loan of $2.016
billion, to be released in six parcels by February 1992.
   The government also outlined goals for growth, the budget
deficit and reducing 4,274% inflation.
   Some of the targets are: negative growth of 3% for gross
national product this year; a spending surplus of 0.5% of GNP
this year and 0% in 1991; 25% annual inflation in 1991; a
reduction of the deficit of government-owned companies from
2.5% of GNP in 1989 to 1% this year and 0% in 1991.
</TEXT>
