<HL>
   Greenspan Sees
   No S&amp;L Crisis
   For U.S. Banks
   ---
   But Fed Chairman Backs
   Rise in Insurance Fees,
   Citing Industry's Woes
   ----
   By Hilary Stout
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Although the nation's banks face serious
problems, the industry isn't headed for a disaster on the
magnitude of the savings-and-loan crisis, Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan said.
   Testifying before the House Banking Committee, Mr.
Greenspan endorsed the idea of raising banks'
deposit-insurance premiums, a move that the administration
and an increasing number of lawmakers support.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Greenspan also reiterated that the Fed would probably
lower interest rates if Congress and the administration reach
a "credible and enforceable" agreement to reduce the federal
budget deficit. It was the first time the chairman has made
such comments since the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait sent oil
prices soaring and heightened fears of resurgent inflation.
   Government officials have grown increasingly anxious over
the health of the nation's banks in the wake of the
multibillion-dollar thrift bailout. New alarms clanged this
week when two congressional agencies warned that the federal
insurance fund that protects bank depositors was dangerously
low.
   But Mr. Greenspan said the banking industry is much
sounder than its sister thrift industry was several years
ago, when problems that led to the failure of thousands of
S&amp;Ls and the huge taxpayer bailout were beginning to fester.
Banks' levels of capital are higher, he said, and banking
regulation is tougher. He also said bank assets are
shorter-term than those of thrifts, allowing banks to more
easily balance their borrowing costs with lending rates.
   Consequently, the Fed chairman said, "The chance of having
the type of problems with banks that we have with thrifts is
very significantly lower."
   But Mr. Greenspan agreed that the deposit-insurance fund
"is under stress" with fund reserves, as a percentage of
insured deposits, at a record low. He also said banks are
threatened by an increasing number of sour real-estate loans
brought on by a downturn in commercial real estate.
   Mr. Greenspan said he would favor enhancing the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp.'s authority to borrow from the
Treasury to cope with any shortages in the insurance fund
while Congress is working on changes in deposit insurance.
The FDIC currently has a $5 billion line of credit with the
Treasury, but has never used it.
   If insurance premiums are raised, Mr. Greenspan said,
officials must take great care to set a level that wouldn't
push some institutions into insolvency. He suggested the
FDIC, which manages both bank and thrift deposit-insurance
funds, determine a new ceiling on insurance premiums. The
premium on thrift deposits is 23 cents per $100 of deposits,
and the premium for banks is set to rise 4.5 cents next year
to 19.5 cents per $100 of deposits.
   The chairmen of the Banking committees, Sen. Donald Riegle
(D., Mich.) and Rep. Henry Gonzalez (D., Texas), yesterday
introduced bills that would give regulators the authority to
raise bank deposit-insurance premiums.
   There is no question that the insurance fund has led banks
to take risks, knowing that the government would protect
their deposit funds, Mr. Greenspan said. It has also kept
depositors from scrutinizing the soundness of the
institutions they choose to house their money, he said.
   Mr. Greenspan said raising the requirements for bank
capital and strengthening supervision of banks would "go a
long way to eliminate excessive risk-taking by insured
institutions."
   He expressed reservations about reducing the federal
insurance limit of $100,000 per account, another idea gaining
popularity. "If we were starting from scratch, the board
believes it would be difficult to make the case that
deposit-insurance coverage should be as high as its current
$100,000 level," he said.
   Nevertheless, banks, thrifts and millions of households
have made decisions assuming the $100,000 coverage, he said.
"Should Congress decide to lower deposit-insurance limits, a
meaningful transition period would be needed," he suggested.
   Mr. Greenspan also said that in the past "month or two"
banks may have "gone over the line" in restricting their
lending policies. Some banks have tightened lending standards
this year, mostly in commercial real-estate loans, leading to
widespread complaints of a credit squeeze. Mr. Greenspan had
been welcoming the increased prudence, and yesterday
maintained: "A substantial part of the pulling back is good,
not bad."
   Separately, Sen. Alan Dixon (D., Ill.) introduced
legislation that would require the Fed to pay into the
bank-insurance fund interest on the $33 billion the industry
keeps in reserve at the Fed. The interest would provide
roughly $2.5 billion annually to the insurance fund, which
currently stands at $13.2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900914-0121.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Broker Firms
   In Japan Cut
   Profit Forecasts
   ---
   Nomura, Daiwa, Yamaichi
   And Nikko Cite Decline
   In Volume, Lower Prices
   ----
   By Clay Chandler
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<CO>
   J.NOM J.DST J.NKT J.YMS
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Japan's Big Four securities firms -- Nomura
Securities Co., Daiwa Securities Co., Nikko Securities Co.
and Yamaichi Securities Co. -- drastically lowered pretax
earnings projections for the fiscal half year ending Sept.
30.
   Nomura, the world's largest securities firm, said its
pretax profit would drop 50%, to 125 billion yen ($905
million) in the first half of this year from 248.9 billion
yen in the like period last year. Daiwa said its pretax
profit would fall 62%, to about 65 billion yen from 171
billion. Nikko estimated its earnings would decline 73%, to
around 35 billion yen from 130.3 billion, and Yamaichi said
its profit would plunge 75%, to 30 billion yen from 117.9
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The projected profits are about a third of what the firms
previously had forecast.
   Pretax earnings are the clearest indication of the firms'
operating results.
   The sharp revisions underscore the damage to the industry
done by the steep reversals on the Tokyo Stock Exchange this
year. The harm to securities companies is broad. First-half
pretax profits for the 25 securities companies listed on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange are expected to fall an average of 50%,
according to a survey in the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's
largest economic daily.
   Officials at the big Japanese securities houses cite
shrinking trading volume and deflated stock prices as the
main reasons for the declines. On average, two-thirds fewer
stocks are changing hands on the Tokyo exchange each day than
were traded at the end of last year. That bites deeply in
Tokyo because nearly half of securities industry revenue here
comes from equity brokerage commissions.
   Business isn't expected to pick up, either. For the full
year ending March 31, 1991, Nomura pretax profit is seen
falling 43% to 280 billion yen. Net income is predicted to
plummet 41% to 130 billion yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900914-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Forecasters
   At UCLA Predict
   Recession Is Ahead
   ---
   GNP Drop Expected to Begin
   In 1990 Fourth Quarter,
   Last at Least Six Months
   ----
   By Earl C. Gottschalk Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The listless U.S. economy is already
slipping into a full-blown recession that will last for at
least six months, University of California at Los Angeles
business forecasters said.
   The UCLA Business Forecasting Project said it sees a
two-quarter decline in the nation's gross national product,
beginning in the fourth quarter. "Should the predicted
declines occur, it will likely be deemed that the recession
began before the fourth quarter because of the profound
weakness exhibited by the economy during the past few
months," said David G. Hensley, acting director of the
forecast.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   UCLA forecasters at the Anderson Graduate School of
Management predict that real GNP will decline at an annual
rate of 2.4% in the fourth quarter and 3.2% in the first
quarter of 1991.
   The recession forecast is in line with that of many other
economists and forecasters. Blue Chip Economic Indicators
Inc., a Sedona, Ariz., firm that polls 50 economists each
month on their economic forecasts, said that 50% of
economists in a Sept. 10 poll predicted a recession that
would begin in the fourth quarter.
   The UCLA forecast is based on the assumption that a
diplomatic solution will be found to the Persian Gulf crisis.
Should a war begin, higher oil prices could deepen the
downturn, the economists said.
   The UCLA economists see a slow growth in consumer spending
in 1990, 1991 and 1992. Interest rates will begin to drop
this fall in response to the deteriorating economy, Mr.
Hensley said. By mid-1991, the federal funds rate will drop
below 6%. The federal funds rate is the interest rate banks
charge each other on overnight loans to meet the daily
reserve requirement.
   Racked by a softening real estate market and defense and
construction layoffs, California will join the national
economy in recession, Mr. Hensley said. "Although the
California economy is currently performing better than the
national economy, there are abundant signs that growth is
slowing," he added.
   Real gross state product for California is predicted to
grow 1.3% this year, followed by projected gains of 0.6% in
1991, 4.8% in 1992 and 2.1% in 1993, he said.
   The slide in California home construction continues, Mr.
Hensley said, with single-family housing starts currently off
33% from last fall. Home prices increases are expected to be
minimal through 1993, certainly below the rate of consumer
price inflation, he said.
   Meanwhile, construction and defense jobs will continue to
be cut, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900914-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Southland May Be Considering Seeking
   Chapter 11 Status, Thus Risking Bailout
   ----
   By Kevin Helliker
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   SLCTC IYCOY J.SEV
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Southland Corp. extended its debt-swap offer to
bondholders for the third time amid signs it is considering
filing for bankruptcy-court protection, which could
jeopardize a proposed $430 million bailout by its Japanese
partners.
   If the company seeks court protection -- a mark of
dishonor to Japanese businessmen -- Southland would put at
risk its agreement with Ito-Yokado, which operates the
company's 7-Eleven convenience stores in Japan. Ito-Yokado
has agreed to buy 70% of Southland if the company first
restructures its $1.8 billion of publicly traded debt. But
the company has got only partial approval from bondholders
for its debt-swap proposals, making it more likely that
Southland may have to file for Chapter 11 protection.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts in Japan couldn't recall an instance where a
Japanese retailer has acquired a company that filed a
bankruptcy petition. "Southland's in a bind," said Andy
Leinoff, an analyst in the Vermont office of McCarthy
Crisanti &amp; Maffei Inc., a bond research firm. "The Japanese
seem to have an honorable aversion to bankruptcy."
   During the second extension, which ended Wednesday,
Southland made so little progress winning over bondholders
that observers say a pre-packaged bankruptcy-law filing --
wherein holdouts could lose their rights -- is the company's
only hope. At the end of the 18-day period, for instance,
only 49.8% of the company's 16.75%-interest notes had been
tendered, a gain of just 3.5 percentage points from the prior
extension.
   The company remains far short of the 95% approval in each
of five classes of bondholders it needs to complete the
Ito-Yokado bailout. In a pre-packaged filing, by contrast,
Southland would need only two-thirds approval. In a
successful pre-packaged proceeding, a company enters
bankruptcy court with a reorganization plan already drawn up
and approved by creditors representing two-thirds of its
debt. Holdouts are bound by court order to go along with the
plan.
   Nevertheless, in extending their offer 13 days, to Sept.
25, Southland officials reaffirmed their commitment to win
bondholder approval, and refused to discuss a bankruptcy-law
petition as an option.
   In Japan, Ito-Yokado officials extended their buy-out
offer, which was set to expire Sept. 15, to Sept. 25 to
coincide with the new deadline for Southland's debt-swap
offer. But a company spokesman declined to say whether the
company would extend the deadline any further. The spokesman
said he hadn't heard of any Southland proposal for a
pre-packaged filing.
   But the chairman of the Southland bondholder committee
said the company is already seeking Securities and Exchange
Commission approval of a bankruptcy reorganization plan. "The
main reason for this latest extension is that we want to get
well over the two-thirds approval level so that if we go this
pre-packaged bankruptcy route, we can do it quickly," said
John Gordon, president of Deltec Securities Corp. A
pre-packaged proceeding can be completed in a matter of
weeks.
   Mr. Gordon, who has been helping Southland woo holdouts,
said that SEC approval of the plan is expected late next
week. But he said he still hopes that a bankruptcy petition
won't be necessary. "Once bondholders who are taking a
show-me posture see these bankruptcy documents right in front
of their nose, maybe we won't have to do it," he said.
   But Southland still has a long way to go. When the latest
offer expired Wednesday, Southland had received tenders from
holders of 53.42% of its 18% notes, 65.27% of its 16.50%
notes, 67.65% of its 15.75% notes, and 92.67% of its 13.50%
notes. Only holders of the company's preferred stock exceeded
the minimum requirements of the deal, tendering 94.53% of the
shares outstanding. Only two-thirds approval of preferred
shareholders was required.
   "Over the past two weeks, we've succeeded in identifying
the vast majority of Southland security holders who have not
yet tendered their securities," said Clark Matthews, chief
financial officer. Now, he said, "we will intensify our
efforts to urge them to tender their securities."
   If Southland keeps falling short, one alternative to
seeking bankruptcy-law protection would be for Ito-Yokado to
lower its requirement that holders of 95% of all bonds
approve the deal. But that would make owning 70% of Southland
less attractive to Ito-Yokado, because high interest rates
would continue to be paid on the untendered bonds. In any
case, the Ito-Yokado spokesman said the company intended to
keep the 95% approval requirement.
   In Japan, analysts said that Southland's continuing
failure to reach an agreement with its bondholders was
discouraging investment in Ito-Yokado stock. Ito-Yokado
"won't continue to be so generous forever," said Takayuki
Suzuki, senior analyst at Merrill Lynch Japan Inc. Although
Mr. Suzuki said it's unlikely the Japanese retailer would
back out of the offer, the company may toughen its position
before the fourth quarter ends.
   Southland, which owns about 6,700 7-Eleven and other
convenience stores in the U.S. and Canada, went private in a
$4.9 billion leveraged buy-out in late 1987 to avoid a
threatened hostile takeover. But increased competition eroded
sales and profit margins and made it difficult for the
company to service the huge debt from the buy-out. That led
to the buy-out proposal, which would give Ito-Yokado a 70%
stake in Southland. Bondholders would retain 25% of the
company, while the founding Thompson family would get the
remaining 5%.
   Southland went into default on its $1.8 billion of
publicly traded debt in mid-July, but avoided being forced
into filing for bankruptcy-law protection when the bondholder
committee endorsed the terms of the current exchange offer,
the fourth proposed by the company.
   ---
   Yumiko Ono in Tokyo contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
