<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Embarassing Reality
   Of Peculiar Institution
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   Judge Thomas Griesa's review of Robert Goldwin's book
about the Constitution -- "Why Blacks, Women, and Jews Are
Not Mentioned in the Constitution, and Other Unorthodox
Views" -- contains the questionable assertion that ". . .
when abolition (of slavery) finally came, it was the laws and
practices of certain states that needed to be changed, not
the Constitution." (Leisure &amp; Arts, Aug. 22)
   He seems to have forgotten the 13th, 14th and 15th
amendments to the Constitution, all of which specifically
addressed slavery and its consequences. The 13th Amendment
specifically uses the word "slavery," in order to abolish it.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Slavery was not abolished, as Mr. Griesa (or perhaps Mr.
Goldwin) suggests, by changing the laws of a few states. It
was partially abolished by the Abraham's Lincoln's
Emancipation Proclamation and the good offices of the Union
Army; but several slaves states fought on the side of the
Union and other states that had outlawed slavery long before
had done so with grandfather clauses that perpetuated it in
isolated instances. For example, there were still a few
elderly slaves in New Jersey at the outbreak of the Civil
War. It was the 13th Amendment that formally eliminated
slavery.
   The word "slavery" does not appear prior to the 13th
Amendment because the authors of the Constitution preferred
euphemism to defending the indefensible, a not uncommon
political response to embarrassing realities. Even the
slaveholders preferred euphemism, with "servant" being the
favored description for the victims of the Peculiar
Institution.
   That embarrassment was particularly acute because the
members of the Philadelphia convention were otherwise staunch
defenders of human liberty and intended the Constitution to
serve that noble end, and it has, for the most part, in the
ensuing two centuries.
   Edward B. Furey Jr.
   Woodhaven, New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900914-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Stock-Index Arbitrage
   Volume on Big Board
   Is Given for Week
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<CO>
   GE MS BSC Z.CSU
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stock-index arbitrage, the most controversial
form of program trading, accounted for nearly half of all
program trading volume at the New York Stock Exchange during
the final week of August.
   The Big Board reported that program trading strategies
accounted for 12.7% of average daily volume of 127.9 million
shares during the week of Aug. 27 through 31. Some 81.2
million shares traded in program strategies, and 38.9 million
shares, or 47.9% of total program volume, were traded in
stock-index arbitrage strategies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   During the week, Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., a unit of General
Electric Co., traded 15.7 million shares in program
strategies, the most of any firm. Kidder also had the highest
stock-index arbitrage volume, trading 7.9 million shares.
   Among the top five program trading firms for the week were
Morgan Stanley Group Inc. (14 million shares); Susquehanna
Investment Group (8.6 million shares); Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
(8.6 million shares), and CS First Boston Corp. (7.4 million
shares). Susquehanna and Bear Stearns accounted for 58% of
all proprietary program trading on the Big Board, the
exchange said.
</TEXT>
