<HL>
   International Brief -- Rolls-Royce PLC:
   Engine Firm's Pretax Profit
   Was Up 14% in First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   U.RR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   Rolls-Royce PLC, the British airplane engine manufacturer,
reported that pretax profit for the first half rose 14% to
#115 million ($214 million) from #101 million, as buoyant
demand offset the impact of a turn-of-the-year strike.
   The results fell below market expectations, which ranged
between #120 million and #130 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales advanced 42% to #1.59 billion from #1.12 billion a
year earlier.
   Earnings per share, however, slipped 2% to 9.9 pence from
10.1 pence because of the larger number of shares in issue in
the latest period.
   Rolls-Royce, riding a boom in aircraft orders that has
seen earnings improve throughout most of the industry,
benefited during the latest period from a full six-month
contribution from NEI, the engineering company it acquired
early last year.
   "The order book currently stands at a record level of more
than #6 billion and the company continues to gain market
share," Lord Tombs, Rolls-Royce chairman, said.
</TEXT>
