<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                      CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. -- $200 million of 9 1/4% notes due
Oct. 1, 1993, priced at 99.775 to yield 9.338%. The notes
were priced at 115 basis points above the Treasury's
three-year note. Rated Baa-3 by Moody's Investors Service
Inc. and double-B-plus by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue
will be sold through underwriters led by Salomon Brothers
Inc.
                                                                                                       

                      MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   Louisiana -- $198.9 million of general obligation bonds,
Series 1990, due Sept. 1, 1991-2010, via a Lehman Brothers
group. The bonds are rated Baa-1/triple-B-plus, except for
bonds due in 1996-2003, 2004-2006 and 2008-2009, which are
insured and triple-A-rated. They were priced to yield from
6.10% in 1991 to 7.60% in 2009 and 2010.
   Illinois Housing Development Authority -- $118.5 million
of single-family mortgage revenue bonds, Series E and F, due
Feb. 1, and Aug. 1, 1994-2001, 2010, 2017, 2019 and 2024,
tentatively priced by a Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. group to yield
from 6.40% for Series F bonds due in 1994 to 8.00% for Series
E bonds due in 2024. Series E consists of $109.1 million of
bonds. Current interest serial bonds are priced at par to
yield from 6.60% in 1994 to 7.30% in 2001. There are $19.9
million of 7.90% term bonds priced at par due Aug. 1, 2010,
$41.5 million of tender option bonds due Aug. 1, 2019, that
are not formally reoffered and $38.4 million of 8% term bonds
priced at par due Feb. 1, 2024. Series F consists of $9.4
million of bonds. Current interest serial bonds are priced at
par to yield from 6.40% in 1994 to 7.10% in 2001. There are
$3.2 million of 7.65% term bonds priced at par due Aug. 1,
2010, and $4.6 million of 7.70% term bonds priced at par due
Aug. 1, 2017. Interest on the Series E bonds will be treated
as a preference item in calculating the federal alternative
minimum tax. Series F bonds are not subject to the tax.
Ratings of double-A/single-A-plus are expected.
                                                                                                       

                     ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Signet Credit Card Trust 1990-1 -- $430 million of 9%
Class A asset-backed certificates priced by Goldman, Sachs &amp;
Co. at 99 37/64 to yield 9.19%, or 80 basis points above the
Treasury's interpolated four-year and five-year note yields.
The securities have a 4.5-year average life. The securities
are backed by Visa and MasterCard receivables issued by
Signet Bank/Virginia, a unit of Signet Banking Corp. The
senior securities are expected to be rated triple-A by
Moody's and S&amp;P, based on the quality of the underlying loans
and a subordinated class of securities. Goldman also priced
$70 million of 9.40% Class B subordinated asset-backed
certificates at 99 5/8 to yield 9.588%. Those securities are
supported by a letter of credit from Sumitomo Bank Ltd. and
were priced to yield 115 basis points above the Treasury's
five-year note. The Class B issue has a 5.1-year average life
and is expected to be rated single-A-2/single-A.
                                                                                                       

                      EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Republic of Finland (sovereign) -- 250 million European
currency units of 10 1/4% Eurobonds due Oct. 2, 1995, at an
issue price of 101 1/4 via Credit Suisse First Boston Ltd.
Reoffered at a fixed price of 99 5/8. Fees 1 7/8.
   Kingdom of Belgium (sovereign) -- 300 million marks of 9%
bonds due Oct. 9, 1995, priced at 101 3/8 to yield 8.65%, via
Westdeutsche Landesbank Girozentrale. Fees 2.
   Tokai Bank Ltd., Hong Kong branch (Japanese parent) --
$300 million of floating-rate notes through Banque Generale
du Luxembourg N.A., due September 2000, at par via Credit
Suisse First Boston Ltd. Coupon at 0.30 point above
three-month London interbank offered rate for first five
years, except for first and last coupon dates. Short first
coupon payable in November at two-month Libor plus 0.30.
Short last coupon payable at one-month Libor plus 0.30. In
sixth to 10th years, coupon at Libor plus 0.40. Callable at
par every coupon date from 1995. Fees 0.30.
   Hokkaido Takushoku Bank Ltd. (Japan) -- $200 million of
loan participation certificates through Yamaichi
International Deutschland G.m.b.H. with Yamaichi
International as lead manager, priced at par and due
September 2000. Coupon at three-month Libor plus 0.30 point
in first five years, then Libor plus 0.40. Callable at par on
every coupon date from 1995. Fees 0.35.
   Nippon Paint Co. (Japan) -- $150 million of Eurobonds due
Sept. 27, 1994, with equity-purchase warrants indicating a 5
1/8% coupon at par via Nikko Securities Co. (Europe). Each
$10,000 bond carries two warrants exercisable from Oct. 11,
1990, through Sept. 6, 1994, to buy shares at an expected
premium of 2 1/2% to the closing price when terms are fixed
Tuesday. Fees 2 1/4.
   Shell Canada Ltd. (Anglo-Dutch parent) -- 150 million
Canadian dollars of 11 5/8% Eurobonds due Oct. 11, 1995, at
101.60 via Wood Gundy Inc. Fees 1 7/8.
   Credit Local de France (France) -- C$100 million of 11
