<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GREENSPAN SAID U.S. BANKS aren't facing a disaster on the
scale of the S&amp;L debacle, despite the banking industry's
serious problems. The Fed chairman told a House panel that he
also endorses the idea of raising the premiums that banks pay
for deposit insurance, a move that is backed by the
administration and by a growing number of lawmakers.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stocks fell sharply under pressure from program selling
that was sparked by a jump in oil prices and a rumor of
Mideast war. The Dow Jones industrials dropped 43.07 points
to 2582.67. The dollar was sharply lower for the second
straight session.
   ---
   An FDIC audit shows the cost to the government of its 1988
sales of failed savings-and-loans will be as much as $95
billion, rather than a previously estimated $39 billion.
   ---
   Budget negotiations continued with few hints of
breakthroughs on crucial remaining issues, such as Bush's
proposal to cut capital-gains taxes. Still, most of those
close to the discussions remained confident an accord
eventually will be reached.
   ---
   Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco have been asked by the
Soviet Union to supply 34 billion cigarettes, the largest
export order ever for either concern. In exchange, the
companies will receive a combination of hard currency and
barter items.
   ---
   GM and the UAW have settled all but the crucial issues of
job security and health benefits in their contract talks. A
new pact could be reached by tonight's deadline, both sides
said.
   ---
   A probe of program trading by three major exchanges found
no evidence of large-scale illicit activity, said people
familiar with the project.
   ---
   The Strategic Petroleum Reserve would be increased by 33%
to a billion gallons under legislation approved by Congress.
The measure also sets up a pilot reserve for refined
products.
   ---
   The accounting profession, in a reversal, now supports
proposed legislation that would require auditors to notify
regulators of possible illegal actions by company officials.
   ---
   Sales of U.S.-made vehicles gained momentum in early
September, rising 2.5% after a weak August.
                                                                                                       

   Ford scaled back some of its 1991 model price increases,
reducing some Taurus models by more than $600.
   ---
   Southland extended its debt-swap offer for the third time
amid signs that the company may be forced to file for
bankruptcy-court protection to complete a proposed, $430
million bailout by its Japanese partners.
   ---
   Carl Icahn won an unusual bankruptcy-court auction for an
Integrated Resources real estate holding, for which he bid
$44 million.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 123,370,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2582.67, off 43.07; transportation 898.11, off 10.54;
utilities 200.08, off 1.63.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3357.53,
off 1.07.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.15, off 1.10;
spot index 129.24, off 1.09.
   Dollar: 136.20 yen, off 1.89; 1.5677 marks, off 0.0236.
</TEXT>
