<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Tokyo Network
   And CBS Set
   News Venture
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   CBS J.TBS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- CBS Inc. and the Tokyo Broadcasting System
entered into a joint agreement to share news bureaus,
exchange news footage and perhaps co-produce sports and
entertainment programming.
   Under terms of the agreement, the first between a U.S. and
a Japanese network, CBS News and TBS will share facilities,
camera crews and, occasionally, correspondents, throughout
the world. TBS operates full-time news bureaus in locations
where CBS News doesn't have a presence, including Cairo,
Vienna and Seoul, South Korea.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agreement comes as the three major broadcast networks
are struggling to cover world events with severe budget
constraints. The news divisions' budgets are running over
because of rising costs, including those for covering the
crisis in the Middle East. And next year promises little
relief. For instance, the annual budget of NBC News,
estimated at $250 million, is likely to have zero growth next
year, said officials within National Broadcasting Co., a
General Electric Co. unit.
   Co-ventures between U.S. broadcast networks and foreign
news-gathering agencies aren't new. NBC News has a 38%
ownership of Visnews Ltd., and ABC News, a unit of Capital
Cities/ABC Inc., owns 45% of Worldwide Television News, and
the company says it expects to increase its stake to 80% by
Monday.
   Financial terms of the agreement between CBS and TBS, set
to go into effect in April, weren't disclosed. TBS gets
exclusive rights to all CBS News programming, including the
"Evening News with Dan Rather" and "60 Minutes." Currently,
CBS News and TBS share facilities and camera crews in such
locations as Johannesburg, South Africa, and Tokyo.
   CBS officials said no details had been finalized on sports
or entertainment shows that would be co-produced with TBS.
CBS, the No. 3-rated network in prime time, has been
discussing possible co-productions with the British
Broadcasting Corp., although no joint productions between the
two companies have been announced.
   "The centerpiece of this deal is the news," said James A.
Warner, president of CBS Enterprises. "We could do a
miniseries or movie in entertainment. In sports, it could be
sharing coverage or the bidding for an event."
   TBS created the show on which ABC's top-rated "American's
Funniest Home Videos" is based.
   CBS News has "done nothing" to jeopardize its editorial
independence, said John Frazee, vice president of CBS News
services. In fact, TBS distributed copies of the CBS News
Standards and Practices handbook to its personnel. Mr. Frazee
said CBS "hasn't ruled anything out," including the
possibility of TBS correspondents occasionally appearing on
CBS News broadcasts when TBS covers an event and a CBS News
correspondent isn't available. "They have a number of people
who speak excellent English," he said.
   CBS isn't ruling out additional co-ventures with other
foreign broadcasters, Mr. Frazee said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900914-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Accounting Panel
   Clears New Rules
   For Debt Issues
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
SECURITIES (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- An accounting standards body voted to issue
partial new guidelines on the way financial institutions
account for debt securities held as investments.
   In a 15-0 vote at its meeting in Seattle, the Accounting
Standards Executive Committee of the American Institute of
Certified Public Accountants said it would require
institutions to disclose information in the notes to
financial statements about the amortized cost and market
value of debt securities held as investments, as well as the
gross unrealized gains and losses for various categories of
debt securities it identified.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The committee's action represents a scaling back of a more
stringent proposal the banking and accounting industries had
opposed that would have required recognizing changes in the
value of certain of the debt securities held as investments
on the income statement. Currently, debt securities held as
investments are marked at historical cost, while those held
as trading assets are marked to market.
   The accounting panel earlier this week softened its stand
on the proposal after receiving overwhelmingly negative
feedback from banks and accountants. Those groups criticized
the original proposal because they say it would have created
wide swings in earnings of financial institutions, rather
than give investors a clearer picture of the value of debt
securities held, as was intended.
   The panel has yet to decide the issue of when to recognize
a loss when an investment security declines in value. John L.
Kreischer, committee chairman, said the panel would meet with
the Financial Accounting Standards Board, the chief
rule-making body, and staff of the Securities and Exchange
Commission to try to reach a consensus on that issue.
   The new guidelines will apply to all financial statements
for periods ending after Dec. 15. Mr. Kreischer said the
panel would probably issue the statement within 60 days.
   The categories of debt securities addressed by the new
guidelines include those issued by the U.S. Treasury and
other U.S. corporations and agencies, government and
government-agency securities, municipal debt and
mortgage-backed securities.
   Institutions also will be required to disclose the amount
of debt securities due in one year or less, after one year
through five years, five to 10 years and after 10 years. In
each of those categories, the amortized cost and market value
must be disclosed. Proceeds from the sale of debt securities
held as investments and gross realized gains and losses on
such sales also must be disclosed.
   The changes were made as part of an effort to standardize
accounting for debt securities by financial institutions.
They also were prompted by concern about abuses of current
guidelines. Critics say that under existing practice,
financial institutions can enhance their financial profile by
selling securities in which they have a profit while
continuing to carry at cost a different batch of the same
securities in which they have a paper loss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900914-0014
</DOCNO>
